{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox academic | name = Christopher Brooke | honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|CBE|FSA|FBA|FRHistS|size=100%}} | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1927|06|23|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Cambridge]], [[England]]<ref name="Telegraph obituary">{{cite news |title=Professor Christopher Brooke&nbsp;– Obituary |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/12163443/Professor-Christopher-Brooke-obituary.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |access-date=10 September 2017}}</ref> | death_date = {{death date and age|2015|12|27|1927|06|23|df=yes}} | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = British | period = | occupation = | title = [[Dixie Professor of Ecclesiastical History]] (1977–1994) | known_for = | spouse = {{marriage|Rosalind Clark|1951|2014|end=d}} | children = | parents = {{unbulleted list | [[Zachary Nugent Brooke]] | Rosa Grace Brooke}} | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = | era = | language = | discipline = [[Historian]] | sub_discipline = [[Medieval history]], [[ecclesiastical history]] | movement = <!-- Should match the idiologial movement or denomination (for religious), "school" of thought etc. (e.g. "Anglican", "Postmodernist", "Socialist" or "Green" etc. --> | religion = <!-- Religion should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | denomination = <!-- Religious denomination should be supported with a citation from a reliable source --> | alma_mater = [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--Only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | workplaces = {{unbulleted list | [[University of Liverpool]] | [[Westfield College|Westfield College, London]] | [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]]}} | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influences = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | influenced = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | awards = <!--Notable national level awards only--> | website = | footnotes = }} '''Christopher Nugent Lawrence Brooke''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|CBE|FSA|FBA|FRHistS}} (23 June 1927&nbsp;– 27 December 2015) was a British medieval historian. From 1974 to 1994 he was [[Dixie Professor of Ecclesiastical History]] at the [[University of Cambridge]].
==Early life and education== Brooke was the son of [[Zachary Nugent Brooke]] (1883–1946) and his wife Rosa Grace Brooke (1888–1964). Following schooling at [[Winchester College]], Brooke undertook his undergraduate work at [[Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge]], where he studied with [[David Knowles (scholar)|David Knowles]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Professor Christopher Brooke Interview Transcript|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/makinghistory/resources/interviews/Brooke_Christopher.html|website=Making History|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>
==Academic career== Brooke taught at Caius from 1977 to 1994, where he remained a life fellow. He held the position of [[Dixie Professor of Ecclesiastical History]] at Cambridge and before becoming a professor [[emeritus]].<ref name=Who>{{cite web |url=http://www.cai.cam.ac.uk/people/christopher-brooke |title=Professor Christopher Brooke CBE, FBA, Hon VPSA |publisher= Gonville & Caius College |accessdate=31 December 2013 }}</ref>
==Later life== Brooke died on 27 December 2015 at the age of 88.<ref>[http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/obituaries/article4680008.ece Professor Christopher Brooke]</ref>
==Personal life== It was at Cambridge that Brooke met his future wife, fellow medievalist Rosalind Brooke (née Clark) in 1951. She died in 2014.<ref name="Telegraph obituary"/><ref>{{cite web|title=In memoriam: Dr Rosalind Brooke|url=http://www.hist.cam.ac.uk/news/099-in-memorium-dr-rosalind-brooke|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>
